<subSubSection id="C35436B80B19FFD4FF18B8639229A993" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B19FFD4FF18B86393ECAA96" blockId="8.[136,1453,1396,1490]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF18B8639745AAB1" bold="true" box="[136,260,1396,1417]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Ind. Loc.:—</emphasis>
Rocky places in tropical America. “in rupibus Americae, 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FCBAB86295E3AAB2" box="[810,930,1397,1418]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Curassaviae</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FC3EB863925CAAB1" box="[942,1053,1396,1417]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">aliarumque</emphasis>
.” In 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B19FFD4FBDDB8639355AAB1" author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1101,1300,1396,1418]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" refId="ref17638" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1737) Hortus Cliffortianus. Med. Doct. &amp; Ac. Imp. N. C. Soc., Amstelaedami, 518 pp." type="book" year="1737">Linnaeus (1737: 181</bibRefCitation>
no. 1) 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF18B88F96ACAA95" bold="true" box="[136,237,1432,1453]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B19FFD4FF18B88F96ACAA95" box="[136,237,1432,1453]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Lectotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B19FFD4FE14B88E9473AA96" author="Mottram, R." box="[388,562,1432,1454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" refId="ref17790" refString="Mottram, R. (1980) The Mammillaria index. Whitestone Gardens Ltd., Sutton-under-Whitestone-cliffe, Thirsk, 103 pp." type="book" year="1980">Mottram 1980: 51</bibRefCitation>
): 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FDAEB88F9418AA95" bold="true" box="[574,601,1432,1453]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">—</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B19FFD4FDC9B88F94AFAA96" author="Plukenet, L." box="[601,750,1432,1454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" refId="ref17986" refString="Plukenet, L. (1691) Phytographia Sive Stirpium Illustriorum &amp; minus cognitarum Icones tabulis aeneis. Sumptibus auctoris, London, 69 pp." type="book" year="1691">Plukenet (1691</bibRefCitation>
: tab.29 fig.1; image of the 
<typeStatus id="54F5DB910B19FFD4FC7BB88F9202AA96" box="[1003,1091,1432,1454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">lectotype</typeStatus>
available at https://bibdigital.rjb.csic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B19FFD4FF2DB8AB9453AAEA" blockId="8.[136,1453,1396,1490]" box="[189,530,1468,1490]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">es/viewer/13654/?offset=#page=4).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B19FFD4FF18BB179229A993" blockId="8.[136,1452,1536,2031]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF18BB179779A922" bold="true" box="[136,312,1536,1562]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Description:—</emphasis>
Simple or clustering stems, globular to short cylinders, to 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FC4CBB169257A923" box="[988,1046,1537,1563]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="8.0">8 cm</quantity>
diameter and 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FB2FBB169346A923" box="[1215,1287,1537,1563]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
tall (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B19FFD4FAD8BB1693DFA923" box="[1352,1438,1537,1563]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[136,229,1072,1094]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetId="figure-21@14.[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Mammillaria mammillaris (Hoxey 1681.03) growing on black volcanic rocks, Canouan." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420322/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF18BB3296B5A907" box="[136,244,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Tubercles</emphasis>
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FF6ABB329725A907" box="[250,356,1573,1599]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="9.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="7.0">7–12 mm</quantity>
long, conic, green. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FDADBB329434A907" box="[573,629,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Axils</emphasis>
slightly woolly but more densely woolly in flowering zone. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FA83BB329329A907" box="[1299,1384,1573,1599]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Areoles</emphasis>
about 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FF18BB5E968DA95B" box="[136,204,1609,1635]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
diameter, situated on the end of the tubercle. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FD72BB5E953CA95A" box="[738,893,1609,1635]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Radial spines</emphasis>
10–16, spreading, 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FBCBBB5F92FBA95B" box="[1115,1210,1608,1635]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="6.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="5.0">5–8 mm</quantity>
long, light brown or greyish. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF79BB7A97CDA9BE" box="[233,396,1645,1671]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Central spines</emphasis>
similar to radials, 3–6, to 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FD26BB7A94B9A9BF" box="[694,760,1645,1671]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
long, reddish-brown. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FC61BB7A9204A9BF" bold="true" box="[1009,1093,1645,1671]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Flower</emphasis>
small, 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FB08BB7A9350A9BF" box="[1176,1297,1645,1671]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
long, creamy white, barely emerging beyond spines. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FDAFBB87943CA992" bold="true" box="[575,637,1680,1706]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Fruit</emphasis>
clavate, red, 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FC83BB8695CDA993" box="[787,908,1681,1707]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="10.0">10–20 mm</quantity>
long. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FC42BB869253A993" box="[978,1042,1681,1707]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Seeds</emphasis>
brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35436B80B19FFD4FF2DBBA393CBA8D7" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B19FFD4FF2DBBA39274A867" blockId="8.[136,1452,1536,2031]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF2DBBA39495A9F6" bold="true" box="[189,724,1716,1743]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
Distribution in the study area (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B19FFD4FDD8BBA394E7A9F6" box="[584,678,1716,1742]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[185,1410,205,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[170,1417,190,1928]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of cacti on Barbados, Grenada, Saint Vincent and the Grenadine islands based on observations by the authors. A. Acanthocereus tetragonus. B. Cereus repandus. C. Mammillaria mammillaris. D. Melocactus broadwayi. E. Melocactus intortus. F. Opuntia dillenii. G. Pilosocereus curtisii H. Selenicereus plumieri I. Opuntia dillenii (Barbados). J. Pilosocereus barbadensis (Barbados)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420304/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
):—
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B19FFD4FD44BBA29243A9F7" authorityName="Karsten" authorityYear="1882" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" box="[724,1026,1717,1743]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Mammillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mammillaris">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FD44BBA29243A9F7" box="[724,1026,1717,1743]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Mammillaria mammillaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not occur in the main islands of 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FF39BBCE9749A9CB" box="[169,264,1753,1779]" name="Grenada" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Grenada</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FED4BBCE979FA9CB" box="[324,478,1753,1779]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Saint Vincent</collectingCountry>
but plants were particularly plentiful on Union island, growing on rocky crags. The northernmost locality known to us is at the northern point of Bequia. This is almost certainly the northernmost locality of this species, as it has not been found further north in the Lesser Antilles. The species is easily overlooked and it probably has a wider distribution than our observations indicate on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FCEBBA529270A867" box="[891,1073,1861,1887]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">The Grenadines</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B19FFD4FF2DBA7F93CBA8D7" blockId="8.[136,1452,1536,2031]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B19FFD4FF2DBA7F979BA8BA" bold="true" box="[189,474,1896,1922]" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">General distribution:—</emphasis>
Outside of the Lesser Antilles, this species is found in the Dutch Antilles and also on mainland South America, in 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FE5BBA9A9478A89F" box="[459,569,1933,1959]" name="Colombia" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FDE0BA9A94A2A89F" box="[624,739,1933,1959]" name="Venezuela" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(and offshore islands). The nearest population is reported from Patos Island, now a possession of 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FD93BAA69437A8F3" box="[515,630,1969,1995]" name="Venezuela" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
but formally part of 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B19FFD4FCCDBAA69207A8F3" box="[861,1094,1969,1995]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="8" pageNumber="33">Trinidad and Tobago</collectingCountry>
[Patos Island, 1931, Rasool s.n. TRIN 12566!], about 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B19FFD4FEECBAC2978AA8D7" box="[380,459,2005,2031]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="33" unit="km" value="180.0">180km</quantity>
from Ronde Island, the southernmost population that we know in the Lesser Antilles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF3135BB0B18FFD5FF18BAF19518A8C4" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420308" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5420308" box="[136,857,2022,2044]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420308/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="34" startId="9.[136,229,2022,2044]" targetBox="[190,1397,190,1998]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B18FFD5FF18BAF19518A8C4" blockId="9.[136,857,2022,2044]" box="[136,857,2022,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="34">
